04195nam a22007215i 9780231520560DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011025624  a97802315205607 a10.7312/step149202doi  a(DE-B1597)459357  a(OCoLC)979751708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHQ1190b.S754 2011 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a306.8743011 aStephens, Julie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConfronting Postmaternal Thinking :bFeminism, Memory, and Care /cJulie Stephens. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Unmothering -- t2. Feminist Reminiscence -- t3. Memory and Modernity -- t4. Maternalism Reconfigured? -- tConclusion: Toward a New Feminist Maternalism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere is a deep cultural anxiety around public expressions of maternalism and the application of maternal values to society as a whole. Julie Stephens examines why postmaternal thinking has become so influential in recent decades and why there has been a growing unease with maternal forms of subjectivity and maternalist perspectives. In moving beyond policy definitions, which emphasize the priority given to women's claims as employees over their political claims as mothers, Stephens details an elaborate process of cultural forgetting that has accompanied this repudiation of the maternal.Reclaiming an alternative feminist position through an investigation of oral history, life narratives, Web blogs, and other rich and varied sources, Stephens confronts the core claims of postmaternal thought and challenges dominant representations of feminism as having forgotten motherhood. Deploying the interpretive framework of memory studies, she examines the political structures of forgetting surrounding the maternal and the weakening of nurture and care in the public domain. She views the promotion of an illusory, self-sufficient individualism as a form of social unmothering that is profoundly connected to this ethos. In rejecting both traditional maternalism and the new postmaternalism, Stephens challenges prevailing paradigms and makes way for an alternative feminist maternalism centering on a politics of care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCollective memory. 0aFeminist theory. 0aMotherhoodxPolitical aspects. 0aMotherhoodxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/step1492040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231520560423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231520560/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK